Split 0:
But: créer un framework équivalent à spring mvc
j'ai besoin de 2 espaces de travail  différent: le framework qui va sortir le .jar et le test
on a donc besoin que de FrontControllerServlet avec 2 fonctions qui sont les suivantes:
doGet -> ProcessRequest
doPost -> PrintWriter [Out.print(Url)]
du coup par exemple le framework crée servlet
et le test prend le jar (class path) c'est l'application test qu'on va déployer dans tomcat après'
package
Par contre les codes du test ne se trouve pas dans le même projet que le framework

Create project root directory for the new implementation (e.g., new-project/)
Set up the framework module: src/main/java/com/framework/annotation/Controller.java (custom @Controller annotation)
Implement utility class for scanning annotated controllers (ClasseUtilitaire) using Reflections library
Implement FrontControllerServlet extending HttpServlet that init() scans controllers and stores their names
Add doGet/doPost delegating to processRequest which prints requested URI and list of controller names
Create Maven pom.xml for framework (jar packaging) with dependencies: jakarta.servlet-api (provided), org.reflections
Set up test application module: src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/web.xml mapping FrontControllerServlet to /*
Create sample controller classes annotated with @Controller (different values) in src/main/java/com/app/controller/
Create Maven pom.xml for test app (war packaging) depending on the framework module
Add deployment scripts (deployFramework.sh, deployTestApplication.sh) that build JAR/WAR and copy to Tomcat webapps
Write a brief README.md explaining the project structure, build steps (mvn clean install/package), and deployment on Tomcat
Optional: Add assets/ and brouillon/ folders with structure.txt and comprehension.md for documentation
Verify the implementation by building both modules and deploying the WAR to a local Tomcat instance